---

<ToolLayout
  title="PDF to Images Converter | Webutilbox"
  description="Convert PDF pages to high-quality images (PNG, JPG) directly in your browser. No upload required. Free online PDF to image converter tool."
  canonical={canonical}
  ogImage="https://webutilbox.com/assets/og/og-pdf-tools.svg"
  keywords="pdf to image, image to pdf, pdf converter, jpg to pdf, png to pdf"
  h1="📄 PDF → Images"
  subtitle="Convert PDF to images or combine images into PDF."
  lastUpdated=""
  shareText="Free%20online%20PDF%20to%20Images%20Converter%20%7C%20Webutilbox%20on%20Webutilbox.%20Privacy-focused%2C%20runs%20100%25%20in%20your%20browser."
  shareUrl={canonical}
  embedUrl={canonical}
  embedTitle="PDF to Images Converter -- Webutilbox"
  embedHeight={600}
  toolCss={true}
  jsonLd={jsonLd}
>

<div id="pdfToImagesMode" class="workspace">
            <!-- Upload PDF -->
            <div style="text-align: center; padding: 40px; border: 2px dashed var(--border); border-radius: 12px; background: var(--light); margin-bottom: 20px;">
                <div style="font-size: 3rem; margin-bottom: 15px;">📄</div>
                <input type="file" id="pdfFile" accept=".pdf" style="display: none;" onchange="loadPDFForConversion()">
                <button class="btn btn-primary" onclick="document.getElementById('pdfFile').click()" style="padding: 15px 30px;">
                    Select PDF File
                </button>
                <p style="margin-top: 10px; font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--gray);">Choose a PDF to convert to images</p>
            </div>

            <!-- PDF Options -->
            <div id="pdfOptions" style="display: none;">
                <div style="background: var(--light); border-radius: 12px; padding: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; border: 1px solid var(--border);">
                    <h3 style="font-size: 1rem; margin-bottom: 15px;">PDF Information</h3>
                    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(150px, 1fr)); gap: 15px; margin-bottom: 20px;">
                        <div>
                            <div style="font-size: 0.8rem; color: var(--gray);">Total Pages</div>
                            <div id="pdfPageCount" style="font-weight: 600; font-size: 1.2rem; color: var(--primary);"></div>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <div style="font-size: 0.8rem; color: var(--gray);">File Name</div>
                            <div id="pdfFileName" style="font-weight: 600; word-break: break-all;"></div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <!-- Conversion Options -->
                    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: 15px; margin-bottom: 20px;">
                        <div>
                            <label style="font-size: 0.85rem; margin-bottom: 6px; display: block;">Image Format</label>
                            <select id="imageFormat" style="width: 100%; padding: 10px;">
                                <option value="png">PNG (Higher Quality)</option>
                                <option value="jpeg">JPEG (Smaller Size)</option>
                            </select>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <label style="font-size: 0.85rem; margin-bottom: 6px; display: block;">Quality (JPEG only)</label>
                            <input type="range" id="imageQuality" min="0.1" max="1" step="0.1" value="0.9" style="width: 100%;">
                            <div style="text-align: center; font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--gray);"><span id="qualityValue">90</span>%</div>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <button class="btn btn-success" onclick="convertPDFToImages()" style="width: 100%; padding: 15px;">
                        🖼️ Convert to Images
                    </button>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Images to PDF Mode -->
        <div id="imagesToPdfMode" class="workspace" style="display: none;">
            <!-- Upload Images -->
            <div style="text-align: center; padding: 40px; border: 2px dashed var(--border); border-radius: 12px; background: var(--light); margin-bottom: 20px;">
                <div style="font-size: 3rem; margin-bottom: 15px;">🖼️</div>
                <input type="file" id="imageFiles" accept="image/*" multiple style="display: none;" onchange="loadImages()">
                <button class="btn btn-primary" onclick="document.getElementById('imageFiles').click()" style="padding: 15px 30px;">
                    Select Images
                </button>
                <p style="margin-top: 10px; font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--gray);">Select multiple images (JPG, PNG, WebP, etc.)</p>
            </div>

            <!-- Image List -->
            <div id="imageList" style="display: none;">
                <div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center; margin-bottom: 15px;">
                    <h3 style="font-size: 1rem; margin: 0;">Selected Images (<span id="imageCount">0</span>)</h3>
                    <button class="btn" onclick="clearImages()" style="padding: 8px 16px;">Clear All</button>
                </div>

                <div id="imageItems" style="background: var(--light); border-radius: 12px; padding: 15px; border: 1px solid var(--border); margin-bottom: 20px;">
                </div>

                <!-- PDF Options -->
                <div style="background: var(--light); border-radius: 12px; padding: 20px; margin-bottom: 20px; border: 1px solid var(--border);">
                    <h3 style="font-size: 1rem; margin-bottom: 15px;">PDF Options</h3>
                    <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(200px, 1fr)); gap: 15px; margin-bottom: 20px;">
                        <div>
                            <label style="font-size: 0.85rem; margin-bottom: 6px; display: block;">Page Size</label>
                            <select id="pageSize" style="width: 100%; padding: 10px;">
                                <option value="a4">A4 (210 × 297 mm)</option>
                                <option value="letter">Letter (8.5 × 11 in)</option>
                                <option value="a3">A3 (297 × 420 mm)</option>
                                <option value="auto">Auto (fit to image)</option>
                            </select>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <label style="font-size: 0.85rem; margin-bottom: 6px; display: block;">Image Fit</label>
                            <select id="imageFit" style="width: 100%; padding: 10px;">
                                <option value="contain">Fit (maintain aspect ratio)</option>
                                <option value="cover">Fill (may crop)</option>
                                <option value="stretch">Stretch (may distort)</option>
                            </select>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <button class="btn btn-success" onclick="convertImagesToPDF()" style="width: 100%; padding: 15px;">
                        📄 Create PDF
                    </button>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Progress -->
        <div id="progress" style="display: none; background: var(--light); border-radius: 12px; padding: 20px; border: 1px solid var(--border); text-align: center; margin-top: 20px;">
            <div style="font-size: 2rem; margin-bottom: 10px;">⏳</div>
            <div id="progressText" style="font-size: 1rem; color: var(--gray);">Processing...</div>
        </div>

        
        <!-- Share Bar -->

<style is:global>
.mode-tab {
            padding: 10px 20px;
            background: var(--dark);
            border: 1px solid var(--border);
            border-radius: 6px;
            color: var(--white);
            cursor: pointer;
            font-size: 0.9rem;
            font-weight: 500;
            transition: all 0.2s;
        }
        .mode-tab:hover {
            background: rgba(249, 115, 22, 0.1);
            border-color: var(--primary);
        }
        .mode-tab.active {
            background: var(--primary);
            border-color: var(--primary);
        }
        .image-item {
            display: flex;
            align-items: center;
            gap: 15px;
            padding: 12px;
            background: var(--dark);
            border-radius: 8px;
            margin-bottom: 10px;
            cursor: move;
        }
        .image-item:hover {
            background: rgba(249, 115, 22, 0.1);
        }
        .image-preview {
            width: 60px;
            height: 60px;
            object-fit: cover;
            border-radius: 6px;
            border: 1px solid var(--border);
        }
</style>


<script src="/js/pdf-images-converter.js" defer></script>

<div class="info-section" slot="info">

            <div class="related-tools">
                <h3>Related Tools</h3>
                <div class="related-tools-grid">
                    <a href="../pdf-merger/" class="related-tool-link">PDF Merger</a>
                    <a href="../pdf-splitter/" class="related-tool-link">PDF Splitter</a>
                    <a href="../image-compressor/" class="related-tool-link">Image Compressor</a>
                    <a href="../image-format-converter/" class="related-tool-link">Image Format Converter</a>
                    <a href="../image-resizer/" class="related-tool-link">Image Resizer</a>
                </div>
            </div>

<h2>PDF to Images Converter - Convert PDF Pages to JPG or PNG</h2>
            <p>Our free PDF to Images Converter lets you extract every page of a PDF as a high-quality JPG or PNG image, or combine multiple images into a single PDF document. Both conversions happen entirely in your browser — no uploads, no waiting, no file size limits imposed by a server.</p>

            <h3>What Is a PDF to Images Converter?</h3>
            <p>A PDF to images converter extracts the visual content of each page in a PDF file and saves it as a raster image (JPG or PNG). This is useful when you need to share individual pages as images, embed PDF content in a presentation, or use PDF pages in applications that don't support PDF files directly.</p>
            <p>The reverse operation — combining images into a PDF — is equally useful. If you have a series of scanned pages, photos, or screenshots that you want to share as a single document, converting them to a PDF creates a professional, universally compatible file that preserves the order and layout of your images.</p>
            <p>This tool uses PDF.js (Mozilla's open-source PDF rendering engine) for PDF-to-image conversion and pdf-lib for image-to-PDF creation. Both libraries run entirely in the browser, so your files never leave your device.</p>

            <h3>PDF to Image Conversion Options</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>PDF to Images: converts every page of a PDF to JPG or PNG format</li>
                <li>Images to PDF: combines multiple images (JPG, PNG, WebP) into a single PDF</li>
                <li>Choice of output format: PNG for higher quality, JPEG for smaller file size</li>
                <li>Adjustable JPEG quality from 10% to 100%</li>
                <li>High-resolution rendering at 2x scale for sharp, clear output images</li>
                <li>Page size options for PDF creation: A4, Letter, A3, or auto-fit to image</li>
                <li>Image fit options: contain (letterbox), cover (crop), or stretch</li>
                <li>Drag-and-drop reordering of images before PDF creation</li>
                <li>Displays PDF page count and file name before conversion</li>
                <li>All processing is local — no server uploads required</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>How to Use the PDF to Images Converter</h3>
            <p>The tool has two modes. Here's how to use each one:</p>
            <ul>
                <li>PDF to Images — Step 1: Click the "PDF to Images" tab and select your PDF file.</li>
                <li>PDF to Images — Step 2: Choose your output format (PNG or JPEG) and quality level.</li>
                <li>PDF to Images — Step 3: Click "Convert to Images". Each page will be downloaded as a separate image file.</li>
                <li>Images to PDF — Step 1: Click the "Images to PDF" tab and select your image files (you can select multiple at once).</li>
                <li>Images to PDF — Step 2: Drag and drop images in the list to reorder them as needed.</li>
                <li>Images to PDF — Step 3: Choose your page size and image fit option, then click "Create PDF" to download the combined PDF.</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Extracting Images from PDFs</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Extracting individual pages from a PDF to use as images in presentations or documents</li>
                <li>Converting PDF reports or brochures to images for sharing on social media</li>
                <li>Combining scanned document pages into a single PDF for archiving or sharing</li>
                <li>Creating a PDF portfolio from a collection of image files</li>
                <li>Converting PDF pages to images for use in web pages or apps that don't support PDF</li>
                <li>Merging multiple screenshots or photos into a single PDF document</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Getting High-Quality PDF Images</h3>
            <p>When converting PDF to images, choose PNG format for documents with text, diagrams, or sharp graphics — PNG is lossless and preserves crisp edges. Use JPEG for PDFs that are primarily photographic content, where the smaller file size outweighs the slight quality reduction from compression.</p>
            <p>The converter renders pages at 2x scale by default, which produces images at twice the PDF's native resolution. This ensures the output images are sharp and readable, especially for text-heavy documents. If you need smaller file sizes, use JPEG format with a quality setting of 70–80%, which provides a good balance between quality and size.</p>
            <p>When creating a PDF from images, use the "Fit" (contain) option to preserve the aspect ratio of your images without cropping. If all your images are the same size and orientation, the "Auto" page size option will create a PDF where each page exactly matches the image dimensions, with no white borders.</p>

            

            <h3>PDFs Processed Locally — Never Uploaded</h3>
            <p>PDF conversion runs in your browser via PDF.js. Your files are never uploaded.</p>
        
            <h3>Frequently Asked Questions</h3>
            <div class="faq-list">
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I convert a PDF to individual images?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes. Upload a PDF and the tool extracts each page as a separate PNG image. You can download all pages as a ZIP file or download individual pages. The output resolution can be adjusted for higher or lower quality images.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Can I convert images back into a PDF?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes. Upload multiple images (PNG, JPG, WebP) and the tool combines them into a single PDF, with each image on its own page. You can reorder the images before converting.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What resolution should I use for PDF to image conversion?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>For screen viewing, 96-150 DPI is sufficient. For printing, use 300 DPI. For high-quality archival, use 600 DPI. Higher DPI produces larger files but sharper images. The default setting works well for most use cases.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why does my converted image look blurry?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>PDF pages contain vector graphics and text that render sharply at any size. When converting to a raster image (PNG/JPG), the resolution setting determines sharpness. Increase the DPI setting for a sharper output image.</p></div>
                </div>
                <div class="faq-item">
                    <button class="faq-question" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Does the tool preserve PDF text as selectable text in images?</button>
                    <div class="faq-answer"><p>No. Converting a PDF to an image produces a raster (pixel-based) image. Text in the image is no longer selectable or searchable — it is just pixels. If you need selectable text, keep the PDF format or use OCR software to extract text from the image.</p></div>
                </div>
            </div>
</div>
</div>

</ToolLayout>